  "prompt": "How do you say thank you in Arabic? Does it depend on who you're speaking to?",
  "response": "In Arabic, the most common way to say \"thank you\" is **\"\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b\" (Shukran)**. This is a general and polite way to express gratitude and can be used in most situations, whether speaking to someone older, younger, or of the same age.\n\nHowever, like in many languages, the level of politeness or formality can be adjusted depending on the context or the person you're speaking to. Here are some variations:\n\n1. **\"\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u062c\u0632\u064a\u0644\u0627\u064b\" (Shukran jazeelan)**  \n   - This means \"Thank you very much\" and adds more emphasis and politeness.\n\n2. **\"\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0641\u064a\u0643\" (Baraka Allahu feek)**  \n   - This is a more formal and religious way to say thank you, meaning \"May Allah bless you.\" It\u2019s often used in more respectful or heartfelt situations.  \n   - For addressing a female, you\u2019d say **\"\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0641\u064a\u0643\u0650\" (Baraka Allahu feeki)**.\n\n3. **\"\u0623\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0643\" (Ashkuruka)**  \n   - This means \"I thank you\" and can be slightly more formal or personal.  \n   - For addressing a female, you\u2019d say **\"\u0623\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0643\u0650\" (Ashkuruki)**.\n\nSo while **\"\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b\" (Shukran)** works in most cases, these variations allow you to express gratitude with different levels of formality or depth.",
